    "troubleshooting": [
      {
        "symptom": "Lumps of green powder in the finished pie",
        "likely_cause": "Matcha powder was not sifted or whisked thoroughly into dry ingredients.",
        "prevention": "Sift matcha with the flour and sugar before adding liquids.",
        "fix": "The straining step in the instructions will remove most lumps before baking."
      },
      {
        "symptom": "Custard is cracked or rubbery",
        "likely_cause": "The pie was overbaked or the oven temperature was too high.",
        "prevention": "Check for doneness at 45 minutes; the center should still jiggle slightly.",
        "fix": "Cover cracks with whipped cream before serving."
      }
    ],
    "chef_notes": [
      "Use high-quality, culinary-grade matcha for the best flavor and vibrant green color. Ceremonial grade matcha is too delicate and expensive for baking.",
      "Sifting the dry ingredients, especially the matcha powder, is crucial for a smooth, lump-free custard. Consider sifting them together twice.",
      "Don't overbake the pie. The center should still have a slight wobble when gently shaken, as it will continue to set as it cools. Overbaking can lead to a rubbery texture.",
      "Allow the pie to cool completely at room temperature before refrigerating. This helps prevent condensation and ensures the custard sets properly."
    ],
    "cultural_context": "While the concept of custard pies is deeply rooted in American baking traditions, the inclusion of matcha powder introduces a distinctly Japanese element. This fusion reflects a modern culinary trend of incorporating global flavors into familiar formats, creating a sophisticated dessert that appeals to a wide audience.",
